column6: It averaged 113.6 points in January 2023 and has been in steady decline since March 2022

Repeating my forecast. The Jan value is 113.6, down 0.1 from Dec 2022. January saw a decline for the 7th month in a row. I expect the decline to continue in February, but since 114 is so close to the current value, I'll leave a substantial possibility of bin 3.

I'm late to the party on this question. The meat index isn't too volatile. The index has declined gently since June and is at 117.1 for Nov. Since June, the index has declined each month by 1.8, 3.0, 0.8, 2.1, and 1.1. Over the past 13 months, the index has ranged from 111.0 to 125.9. I expect the index to continue to trend gently downward over the next 3 months, perhaps by 1.0 to 7.0 overall. I don't think a sharp rise in prices that would put the result over 123.0 is likely.

Updating w/ September index: lower for meats, despite avian flu still an issue in the US and EU, pork prices rising in China, while the ongoing liquidation of beef in US is probably adding some pressure. I'd expect higher prices until Jan/23.

Updating w/ August index: slightly lower than my forecast, though I still believe poultry production should increase in the short term, demand seasonality and problems with avian flu, along higher prices for hog in China, may push this index higher until the end of the year.

Updating w/ July index: slightly higher than expected, but still following the same trends, though with lower grain prices we could see production ramping up faster this semester, especially for poultry.
railroads already holding back shipments of fodder for feed lots and if they go on strike Mondy (RR) the price of corn fed beef will rocket.
Updating w/ June index: I expected 124.7 for meat in June, so the index came flat.

Updating with May index: I was expecting a downturn in beef prices, with pork flat and poultry on an uptrend, but I was surprised by the resilience of beef prices. With slaughter increasing in Brazil, prices should accommodate, but FX rate may play a more significant role here. I'm adjusting for a mostly flat 2nd semester with beef lower, pork and poultry higher.

Despite the April update of FAO's Food Index for meat coming 2% lower than my previous projection, my forecast for Feb 23 didn't change much, maybe removing the possibility of a spike above 150. Bird flu situation is still an ongoing issue and should have a significant impact in US and EU, adding to the push from costs (corn and soybean). At the same time, pork prices seem to have reached a plateau after spiking in US and EU, though there are some early signs that prices started to go up in China. Beef prices should drop in the US, maybe not in Q2, but in 2H22, the same trend in South America though for different reasons.

The index is up about a third from a year ago and the increase seems highly related to the Russian war on Ukraine. Perhaps there was an initial shock that may moderate a bit. More likely it relates to taking Ukrainian agricultural products off the market. I suspect the war will continue past May and Russian parade needs. If the war continues and even expands, there is reason to suspect that the index will increase much further over its current levels.
